\section*{14. Gradient Flow and Scale Setting}

The gradient flow provides a way to define a continuous scale on the lattice by evolving the gauge field in a fictitious flow time dimension.

\subsection*{14.1 Wilson Flow Definition}

The Wilson flow is defined by the differential equation:

\begin{equation}
	\frac{dU_\mu(x, t)}{dt} = - \langle G_\mu(x, t) \rangle U_\mu(x, t)
\end{equation}

The energy density at flow time $t$ is defined as:

\begin{equation}
	E(t) = \frac{1}{V} \sum_{x} \sum_{\mu<\nu} \left[ 1 - \frac{1}{3} \text{Re Tr}[P_{\mu\nu}(x)] \right] = 6.0 - P(t)
\end{equation}

The physical energy density requires normalization: $E_{\text{phys}}(t) = \beta \cdot E(t)$

The scale $t_0$ is defined by:
\begin{equation}
	t_0^2 \langle E(t_0) \rangle = 0.3
\end{equation}

The physical scale is related by $\sqrt{8t_0} \approx 0.415$ fm.

\subsection*{14.2 Static Quark Potential and Sommer Parameter}

The static quark potential $V(r)$ is extracted from Wilson loops:
\begin{equation}
	W(r, t) = A(r) \exp(-V(r)t)
\end{equation}

The potential is fit to the Cornell form:
\begin{equation}
	V(r) = -\frac{A}{r} + \sigma r + C
\end{equation}

The Sommer parameter $r_0$ is defined by $r_0^2 F(r_0) = 1.65$:
\begin{equation}
	r_0 = \sqrt{\frac{1.65 - A}{\sigma}}
\end{equation}

Physical value: $r_0 \approx 0.5$ fm, giving $a = 0.5\text{ fm} / (r_0/a)$.

\subsection*{14.3 Results: Lattice Size Comparison at $\beta=5.7$}

